  "response": "As of April 2023, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has announced the withdrawal of the Rs 2000 currency notes, but there is no official confirmation about the inclusion of a nano GPS chip in these notes.\n\nHere are some key points:\n\n1. Withdrawal of Rs 2000 notes:\n- The RBI announced that Rs 2000 notes can be deposited or exchanged until September 30, 2023\n- These notes will be withdrawn from circulation\n\n2. Claims about GPS chips:\n- There have been rumors and social media claims about GPS chips in currency notes\n- However, these claims are generally considered to be unsubstantiated\n\n3. Technical challenges:\n- Embedding a functional GPS chip in a thin banknote is technically complex\n- Such technology would be extremely expensive to implement on a large scale\n- Practical limitations exist in terms of power supply and signal transmission\n\n4. Existing anti-counterfeiting measures:\n- Currency notes already have several security features like:\n  - Watermarks\n  - Security threads\n  - Micro-printing\n  - Holographic strips\n  - Color-shifting ink\n\nWhile the idea of GPS tracking sounds appealing, it is currently not a practical or confirmed method for tracking currency notes.",
